1584","1510–Female":"1510–Afdød","1534–1585":"1534–1585","1480–1584":"1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Afdød","1 Jan 1534":"1. januar 1534","22 January 1587":"22. januar 1587","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"omkring 1505","1534":"1534","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","23 May 1584":"23. maj 1584","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Rotingdean, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"nl":{"about 1505–23 May 1584":"circa 1505–23 mei 1584","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1510–Female":"1510–Overleden","1534–1585":"1534–1585","1480–1584":"1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Overleden","1 Jan 1534":"1 januari 1534","22 January 1587":"22 januari 1587","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"circa 1505","1534":"1534","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","23 May 1584":"23 mei 1584","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rotingdean, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"en":{"about 1505–23 May 1584":"about 1505–23 May 1584","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1510–Female":"1510–Deceased","1534–1585":"1534–1585","1480–1584":"1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Deceased","1 Jan 1534":"1 January 1534","22 January 1587":"22 January 1587","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"about 1505","1534":"1534","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","23 May 1584":"23 May 1584","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Rotingdean, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Copper","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent and Surrey): occupational name either from Middle English <i>copere</i>, a variant of <i>cupere</i> ‘cooper, maker or seller of casks, buckets, and tubs’, found late as <i>copper</i>, or from Middle English <i>copper</i>, <i>cupper</i> ‘maker of cups and small vessels’ (Old Norse <i>koppari</i>).","English: in Sussex and perhaps the adjacent counties, probably also a variant of <b>Coppard</b>, either from a Middle English (from Old French, Middle Dutch, or both) personal name <i>Coppard</i> (an extended form of <i>Cop</i>, a pet form of <i>Jacob</i>), or perhaps from Middle English <i>cop(e)</i>, <i>coppe</i> ‘top, head’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>, perhaps for someone with a large head.","Altered form of German   Kopper  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kopper","meanings":["German: from Middle Low German <i>kopper</i> ‘copper’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a copper dealer or coppersmith.","North German: occupational name, from Low German <i>Kopper</i> or <i>Köpper</i> ‘bloodletter’, i.e. someone who applied cups in order to effect a bleeding.","German: from a Germanized form of Slavic <i>kop(e)r</i> (from Old Slavic <i>koprъ</i>) ‘dill, fennel’ (compare   Koper   1), hence a topographic name or a metonymic occupational name for a herb grower or dealer."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":64,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":66,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When George Copper was born about 1505, in England, his father, George Copper, was 27 and his mother, Mrs George Cooper, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Eliza T Roots. He died on 23 May 1584, in Brenchley, Kent, England, at the age of 80, and was buried in Brenchley, Kent, England."},"et":{"about 1505–23 May 1584":"umbes 1505–23. mai 1584","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1534–1585":"1534–1585","1480–1584":"1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","1 Jan 1534":"1. jaanuar 1534","22 January 1587":"22. jaanuar 1587","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"umbes 1505","1534":"1534","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","23 May 1584":"23. mai 1584","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rotingdean, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1505–23 May 1584":"noin 1505–23. toukokuuta 1584","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","1534–1585":"1534–1585","1480–1584":"1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Kuollut","1 Jan 1534":"1. tammikuuta 1534","22 January 1587":"22. tammikuuta 1587","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"noin 1505","1534":"1534","1510":"1510","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","23 May 1584":"23. toukokuuta 1584","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rotingdean, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"fr":{"about 1505–23 May 1584":"environ 1505–23 mai 1584","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1510–Female":"1510–Décédée","1534–1585":"1534–1585","1480–1584":"1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Décédée","1 Jan 1534":"1 janvier 1534","22 January 1587":"22 janvier 1587","1571":"1571","1480":"1480